{"refrec": {"BRefID": 301610, "RR": "<b>Heylen, B.C.; Nachtsheim, D.A.</b> (2018). Bio-telemetry as an essential tool in movement ecology and marine conservation, <b><i>in</i></b>: Jungblut, S. <i>et al.</i> (Ed.) <i>YOUMARES 8 \u2013 Oceans Across Boundaries: Learning from each other: Proceedings of the 2017 conference for YOUng MARine RESearchers in Kiel, Germany.</i> pp. 83-107. <a href=\"https://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_7\" target=\"_blank\">https://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_7</a>", "BEntID": 293851, "PublicFlag": 1, "CheckedFlag": 0, "wosflag": 0, "vabbflag": 0, "RefStringPartII": ", <b><i>in</i></b>: Jungblut, S. <i>et al.</i> <i>YOUMARES 8 \u2013 Oceans Across Boundaries: Learning from each other: Proceedings of the 2017 conference for YOUng MARine RESearchers in Kiel, Germany.</i> pp. 83-107. <a href=\"https://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_7\" target=\"_blank\">https://hdl.handle.net/10.1007/978-3-319-93284-2_7</a>", "DocTypID": 17, "MarineFlag": 1, "FreshFlag": 0, "BrackishFlag": 0, "TerrestrialFlag": 0, "Authorstring": "Heylen, B.C.; Nachtsheim, D.A.", "OrigTitleTranslFlag": 0, "Authorstringtrunc": "Heylen, B.C.; Nachtsheim, D.A.", "Englishabstract": "Marine top predators represent an essential part of marine ecosystems. They are generally regarded as \u201csentinels of the sea\u201d since their presence reflects high biological productivity. However, many populations are experiencing dramatic declines attributed to various human-induced threats (e.g., pollution, climate change, overfishing), highlighting the need for effective conservation. In this review, we show that bio-telemetry can be an essential tool, not only to improve knowledge about the animals\u2019 ecology, but also for conservation purposes. As such, we will first discuss the most important state-of-the-art devices (e.g., time-depth recorders, accelerometers, satellite tags) and illustrate how they can improve our understanding of movement ecology. W